body:
The **diamond operator** `<>` (Java 7+) allows the compiler to infer the generic type arguments from context, reducing verbosity.

Before Java 7:
```java
Map<String, List<Integer>> map = new HashMap<String, List<Integer>>();
```

With diamond operator:
```java
Map<String, List<Integer>> map = new HashMap<>();
```

The compiler infers `<String, List<Integer>>` from the left side.

Java 9 extended diamond inference to anonymous classes:
```java
Comparator<String> c = new Comparator<>() {
    public int compare(String a, String b) { return a.compareTo(b); }
};
```

The diamond operator is purely a compiler feature ‚Äî the bytecode is identical. It reduces typos in complex generic type arguments and keeps the right side cleaner.

