**Generics** allow classes, interfaces, and methods to work with any type while providing compile-time type safety ‚Äî no casts, no `ClassCastException` at runtime.

```java
class Box<T> {
    private T value;
    Box(T value) { this.value = value; }
    T get() { return value; }
}
Box<String> box = new Box<>("hello");
String s = box.get(); // no cast needed
```

**Type parameters** by convention: `T` (type), `E` (element), `K/V` (key/value), `R` (return).

**Wildcards:**
- `?` ‚Äî unknown type
- `? extends T` ‚Äî upper bound (read-only covariance)
- `? super T` ‚Äî lower bound (write-only contravariance)

**Type erasure:** generic type info is erased at runtime. `List<String>` and `List<Integer>` are both `List` at runtime.

examples.code:
public static <T extends Comparable<T>> T max(T a, T b) {
    return a.compareTo(b) >= 0 ? a : b;
}

System.out.println(max(3, 7));       // 7
System.out.println(max("cat", "dog")); // dog

